    <div class="container">
        <h1>UNIT 5: ENVIRONMENTAL LEGISLATION &amp; POLICY</h1>
        <div class="subtitle">UPPCB AEE 2026 | 8-10 Questions | 32-40 Marks | Comprehensive Revision Notes (+ GATE ES Additions)</div>

        <h2>SECTION 1: CONSTITUTIONAL PROVISIONS</h2>
        <div class="section-intro">
            Indian Constitution articles &amp; schedules relevant to environment. Foundation for all environmental laws — guaranteed 1–2 Qs.
        </div>

        <h3>1.1 KEY ARTICLES</h3>
        <table>
            <tr><th>Article</th><th>Provision</th><th>Type</th></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Article 21</strong></td><td>Right to life — interpreted by SC to include <span class="key-point">right to clean &amp; healthy environment</span></td><td>Fundamental Right</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Article 32</strong></td><td>Right to constitutional remedies (Writ jurisdiction in SC)</td><td>Fundamental Right</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Article 48A</strong></td><td>"State shall endeavour to protect &amp; improve environment and to safeguard forests and wildlife"</td><td>DPSP (added by 42nd Amendment, 1976)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Article 51A(g)</strong></td><td>"Fundamental duty of every citizen to protect &amp; improve natural environment, forests, lakes, rivers, wildlife, and have compassion for living creatures"</td><td>Fundamental Duty (42nd Amendment, 1976)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Article 226</strong></td><td>Writ jurisdiction in High Courts</td><td>Constitutional remedy</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Article 253</strong></td><td>Parliament power to make law for implementing international treaties</td><td>Legislative power (basis for E(P) Act 1986)</td></tr>
        </table>
        <div class="highlight">
            <strong>Landmark interpretation:</strong> SC in <em>Subhash Kumar v State of Bihar</em> (1991) held that right to live includes right to enjoyment of pollution-free water and air for full enjoyment of life under Art 21.
        </div>

        <h3>1.2 SEVENTH SCHEDULE — DIVISION OF SUBJECTS</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Union List (List I):</strong> Atomic energy, oilfields/mineral oil resources, regulation of mines</li>
            <li><strong>State List (List II):</strong> Public health, sanitation, water supply, irrigation, fisheries, land</li>
            <li><strong>Concurrent List (List III):</strong> Forests (transferred from State List by 42nd Amendment), protection of wild animals &amp; birds, prevention of cruelty to animals, factories</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>1.3 42ND AMENDMENT (1976) — ENVIRONMENT-RELATED CHANGES</h3>
        <div class="content">
            <ul>
                <li>Added <strong>Article 48A</strong> (DPSP) and <strong>Article 51A(g)</strong> (Fundamental Duty)</li>
                <li>Transferred "Forests" and "Protection of Wild Animals &amp; Birds" from State List to Concurrent List</li>
                <li>This made environment a constitutional priority</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h2>SECTION 2: KEY ENVIRONMENTAL ACTS</h2>
        <div class="section-intro">
            Mother of legislation — Acts. Highest weightage section. Memorise year, sections, penalties.
        </div>

        <h3>2.1 WATER (PREVENTION &amp; CONTROL OF POLLUTION) ACT, 1974</h3>
        <div class="standard">
            <strong>First major environmental Act in India.</strong> Enacted under Article 252 (consent of states), as Water is a State Subject.
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Section 3:</strong> Constitution of CPCB (Central Pollution Control Board)</li>
                <li><strong>Section 4:</strong> Constitution of SPCBs (State Pollution Control Boards)</li>
                <li><strong>Section 16:</strong> Functions of CPCB — coordinate, advise, set standards, training, R&amp;D</li>
                <li><strong>Section 17:</strong> Functions of SPCB — implement standards, grant consent, monitor</li>
                <li><strong>Section 24:</strong> Prohibits use of stream/well for disposal of polluting matter</li>
                <li><strong>Section 25:</strong> <span class="key-point">Consent to Establish (CTE)</span> &amp; <strong>Section 26 (existing units):</strong> mandatory before discharge</li>
                <li><strong>Section 27:</strong> Refusal/withdrawal of consent</li>
                <li><strong>Section 33A:</strong> Power of SPCB to issue directions (closure, electricity/water cut)</li>
                <li><strong>Section 41/43/44:</strong> Penalties — imprisonment 1.5 years to 6 years + fine</li>
                <li><strong>Section 47:</strong> Offences by companies (officers liable)</li>
                <li><strong>Section 49:</strong> Cognisance of offences only by Board or by complaint with 60-day notice</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>2.2 WATER (PREVENTION &amp; CONTROL OF POLLUTION) CESS ACT, 1977</h3>
        <div class="content">
            <ul>
                <li>Levies cess on water consumed by specified industries &amp; local authorities</li>
                <li>Cess collected by State; transferred to Central Govt; reimbursed to SPCBs (up to 80%) for funding</li>
                <li>15 categories of industries (Schedule I): pulp &amp; paper, chemicals, ferrous metals, non-ferrous, sugar, textiles, dye &amp; dye intermediates, etc.</li>
                <li>Rebate of 25% if (a) ETP installed and (b) consumption within standard</li>
                <li><strong>Repealed by GST Council in 2017</strong> (subsumed under GST regime)</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>2.3 AIR (PREVENTION &amp; CONTROL OF POLLUTION) ACT, 1981</h3>
        <div class="standard">
            Enacted under Article 253 (to implement Stockholm Conference 1972).
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Section 16:</strong> Functions of CPCB on air</li>
                <li><strong>Section 17:</strong> Functions of SPCB on air</li>
                <li><strong>Section 19:</strong> Power to declare <strong>Air Pollution Control Areas</strong> (APCAs)</li>
                <li><strong>Section 20:</strong> Power to give instructions on use of fuels in APCAs</li>
                <li><strong>Section 21:</strong> CTE/CTO for industries in APCAs</li>
                <li><strong>Section 22:</strong> Prohibition of emission exceeding standards</li>
                <li><strong>Section 31A:</strong> Power to issue directions (added 1987 amendment, mirrors Water Act 33A)</li>
                <li><strong>Section 37:</strong> Penalty — imprisonment 1.5–6 years + fine</li>
                <li><strong>1987 amendment</strong> brought Noise within Air Act ambit</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>2.4 ENVIRONMENT (PROTECTION) ACT, 1986 ["UMBRELLA ACT"]</h3>
        <div class="standard">
            Passed in aftermath of Bhopal disaster (Dec 2-3, 1984). Most powerful environmental statute.
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Section 3:</strong> Power of Central Govt to take ALL measures for environment protection</li>
                <li>&nbsp;&nbsp;• 3(1) — coordinate state actions, set standards, restrict locations of industries, lay down procedures &amp; safeguards</li>
                <li>&nbsp;&nbsp;• 3(2) — set standards for emissions/discharge</li>
                <li>&nbsp;&nbsp;• 3(3) — constitute authorities (e.g., CRZ Authority, EPCA, CGWA)</li>
                <li><strong>Section 5:</strong> Power to issue directions (closure, electricity/water cut)</li>
                <li><strong>Section 6:</strong> Power to make rules</li>
                <li><strong>Section 7:</strong> No person shall discharge pollutant in excess of standard</li>
                <li><strong>Section 8:</strong> Procedure for handling hazardous substances</li>
                <li><strong>Section 9:</strong> Furnishing information to authorities in case of emergency</li>
                <li><strong>Section 15:</strong> <span class="key-point">Penalty — up to 5 years imprisonment + ₹1 lakh fine; continuing failure ₹5000/day; if &gt; 1 yr, up to 7 years</span></li>
                <li><strong>Section 16:</strong> Offences by companies</li>
                <li><strong>Section 19:</strong> Cognisance only on complaint by Govt OR by any person who has given 60-day notice</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="highlight">
            <strong>Major rules under E(P) Act 1986:</strong> EIA Notification 2006; CRZ Notification 2019; Hazardous Chemicals Rules 1989; HOWM Rules 2016; SWM Rules 2016; Plastic Waste Rules 2016; E-Waste Rules 2022; BMW Rules 2016; Noise Rules 2000; Wetland Rules 2017; Eco-Sensitive Zones; Ozone Depleting Substances (Regulation) Rules 2000.
        </div>

        <h3>2.5 WILDLIFE (PROTECTION) ACT, 1972</h3>
        <div class="content">
            Enacted to implement CITES (1973). Amended several times — latest <strong>Wildlife (Protection) Amendment Act, 2022</strong>.<br/>
            <strong>Schedules (post 2022 amendment — restructured to 4 from earlier 6):</strong>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Schedule I:</strong> animals with highest protection (tiger, lion, elephant, rhinoceros, snow leopard, etc.); penalty for hunting: 3–7 years + fine ₹25,000+</li>
                <li><strong>Schedule II:</strong> animals with reduced protection (some monkeys, civets)</li>
                <li><strong>Schedule III:</strong> protected plants (orchids, kuth, etc.)</li>
                <li><strong>Schedule IV:</strong> CITES Appendix species (added by 2022 amendment)</li>
            </ul>
            <strong>Protected Areas:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>National Park</strong> (NP): no human activity; ~106 in India</li>
                <li><strong>Wildlife Sanctuary</strong> (WLS): some restricted activity allowed; ~573</li>
                <li><strong>Conservation Reserve</strong> &amp; <strong>Community Reserve</strong> (added 2002 amendment)</li>
                <li><strong>Tiger Reserves:</strong> declared under Section 38V (added 2006); ~55 tiger reserves managed by NTCA (Project Tiger 1973)</li>
            </ul>
            <strong>Authorities:</strong> NBWL (National Board for Wildlife) chaired by PM; State Boards; Wildlife Crime Control Bureau (WCCB).
        </div>

        <h3>2.6 FOREST (CONSERVATION) ACT, 1980</h3>
        <div class="standard">
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Section 2:</strong> No State Govt shall (without prior approval of Central Govt) — (a) declare reserved forest as not reserved; (b) use forest land for non-forest purpose; (c) assign forest land to private person; (d) clear naturally grown trees for re-afforestation</li>
                <li><strong>Compensatory Afforestation:</strong> equivalent area of non-forest land OR 2× degraded forest land, plus NPV (Net Present Value) for diversion</li>
                <li><strong>CAMPA</strong> (Compensatory Afforestation Fund Mgmt &amp; Planning Authority) — under CAF Act 2016 — manages CA funds (~₹50,000 crore corpus)</li>
                <li><strong>FCA Amendment 2023</strong> renamed it "Van (Sanrakshan Evam Samvardhan) Adhiniyam" — exempted forest land within 100 km of LAC, security infrastructure up to 10 ha, etc.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>2.7 BIOLOGICAL DIVERSITY ACT, 2002</h3>
        <div class="content">
            Enacted to implement <strong>Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD), 1992 (Rio Earth Summit)</strong>.<br/>
            <strong>Three-tier structure:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>National Biodiversity Authority (NBA):</strong> Chennai; foreign access &amp; IPR clearance</li>
                <li><strong>State Biodiversity Board (SBB):</strong> domestic commercial use approvals</li>
                <li><strong>Biodiversity Management Committee (BMC):</strong> at every panchayat / municipality; maintains <strong>People's Biodiversity Register (PBR)</strong></li>
            </ul>
            <strong>Key concepts:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>ABS (Access &amp; Benefit Sharing):</strong> equitable sharing of benefits from biological resources</li>
                <li><strong>Section 3:</strong> Restriction on foreign nationals/companies for use of biological resources without NBA approval</li>
                <li><strong>Biodiversity Heritage Sites</strong> declared by State Govt</li>
                <li><strong>2023 amendment:</strong> decriminalised some offences; encouraged AYUSH research; faster approvals</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>2.8 NATIONAL GREEN TRIBUNAL (NGT) ACT, 2010</h3>
        <div class="standard">
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Established:</strong> 18 October 2010; first sitting May 2011</li>
                <li><strong>Composition:</strong> Chairperson (sitting/retired SC judge or HC Chief Justice) + judicial &amp; expert members (10 each, max 20 each)</li>
                <li><strong>Principal bench:</strong> New Delhi; <strong>Zonal benches:</strong> Pune (West), Bhopal (Central), Kolkata (East), Chennai (South)</li>
                <li><strong>Jurisdiction:</strong> civil cases related to enforcement of any of <strong>7 environmental laws</strong> in Schedule I:
                    <ol>
                        <li>Water Act 1974</li>
                        <li>Water Cess Act 1977</li>
                        <li>Forest (Conservation) Act 1980</li>
                        <li>Air Act 1981</li>
                        <li>Environment (Protection) Act 1986</li>
                        <li>Public Liability Insurance Act 1991</li>
                        <li>Biological Diversity Act 2002</li>
                    </ol>
                    (Note: Wildlife Protection Act 1972 is NOT under NGT jurisdiction)
                </li>
                <li><strong>Limitation:</strong> 6 months from cause of action (extendable by 60 days)</li>
                <li><strong>Decision:</strong> within 6 months</li>
                <li><strong>Appeal:</strong> directly to Supreme Court within 90 days</li>
                <li><strong>Principles applied:</strong> Sustainable development, Polluter Pays, Precautionary Principle</li>
                <li><strong>Penalty:</strong> non-compliance — up to 3 years jail or ₹10 crore (companies up to ₹25 crore)</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="highlight">
            <strong>Notable NGT orders:</strong> Banned diesel vehicles &gt; 10 yr in NCR (2015); Sterlite Copper closure (2018, Tuticorin); STP discharge standards revision (Jan 2019, 1 mg/L FC for new STPs in metros); Yamuna pollution monitoring; ban on plastic flags.
        </div>

        <h3>2.9 PUBLIC LIABILITY INSURANCE (PLI) ACT, 1991</h3>
        <div class="content">
            Enacted post-Bhopal to provide immediate relief to victims of accidents involving hazardous substances.
            <ul>
                <li>Mandatory insurance by handlers of hazardous substances (listed in HC Rules 1989 — over 600 substances)</li>
                <li><strong>No-fault liability principle:</strong> victims need not prove negligence</li>
                <li>Maximum compensation per claim: ₹25,000 (medical), ₹25,000 (loss of wages), ₹25,000–₹1 lakh (death/permanent disability) — limited; balance through tort law</li>
                <li><strong>Environmental Relief Fund:</strong> contribution by industry equal to insurance premium; managed by Govt</li>
                <li>District Collector adjudicates claims</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>2.10 OTHER KEY LAWS (BRIEF)</h3>
        <table>
            <tr><th>Act</th><th>Year</th><th>Subject</th></tr>
            <tr><td>Indian Forest Act</td><td>1927</td><td>Forest classification (Reserved, Protected, Village)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Atomic Energy Act</td><td>1962</td><td>Radioactive material regulation; AERB</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Insecticides Act</td><td>1968</td><td>Registration &amp; sale of pesticides</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Hazardous Chemicals (Manufacture, Storage &amp; Import) Rules</td><td>1989</td><td>MAH units; on-site &amp; off-site emergency plans</td></tr>
            <tr><td>National Environment Tribunal Act</td><td>1995</td><td>(repealed by NGT Act 2010)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>National Environment Appellate Authority Act</td><td>1997</td><td>(repealed by NGT Act 2010)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Compensatory Afforestation Fund (CAF) Act</td><td>2016</td><td>CAMPA fund management</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Energy Conservation Act</td><td>2001 (amended 2022)</td><td>BEE; star rating; carbon market provisions (2022 amendment)</td></tr>
        </table>

        <h2>SECTION 3: RULES &amp; NOTIFICATIONS</h2>
        <div class="section-intro">
            Subordinate legislation under E(P) Act 1986 — high probability factual Qs.
        </div>

        <h3>3.1 EIA NOTIFICATION 2006</h3>
        <div class="standard">
            Issued under E(P) Act 1986; supersedes EIA Notification 1994.
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Scope:</strong> 8 sectors covering 39 categories of projects (mining, thermal power, river valley, infrastructure, etc.)</li>
                <li><strong>Two categories:</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Category A:</strong> appraised by <strong>EAC (Expert Appraisal Committee)</strong> at central level (MoEFCC)</li>
                        <li><strong>Category B:</strong> appraised by <strong>SEAC (State EAC)</strong> at state level (SEIAA — State Environmental Impact Assessment Authority)</li>
                        <li>Category B further split into <strong>B1</strong> (full EIA required) &amp; <strong>B2</strong> (no EIA, only EMP)</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li><strong>4-stage process:</strong> Screening → Scoping (ToR) → Public Consultation → Appraisal</li>
                <li><strong>Public hearing:</strong> compulsory for Cat A &amp; B1 (except some exempt categories like industrial estates within notified parks)</li>
                <li><strong>Validity of EC:</strong> 5 years (mining 50 years, river valley 13 years, area development 10 years)</li>
                <li><strong>Form 1 + Form 1A</strong> (latter for buildings/area development) — initial application</li>
                <li><strong>EIA Draft Notification 2020</strong> proposed major changes (post-facto clearance, reduced public hearing) — heavily criticised; not finalised</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>3.2 CRZ NOTIFICATION 2019</h3>
        <div class="content">
            Coastal Regulation Zone — 500 m landward from HTL; 50 m on tidal influenced rivers/creeks.<br/>
            <strong>Four CRZ categories:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>CRZ-I:</strong> ecologically sensitive (mangroves, coral reefs, salt marshes, turtle nesting); two sub-zones IA (no construction) &amp; IB (intertidal, limited)</li>
                <li><strong>CRZ-II:</strong> developed urban areas close to shoreline (existing built environment)</li>
                <li><strong>CRZ-III:</strong> rural &amp; undeveloped; A &amp; B sub-zones based on density (A: density &gt; 2161/km²; B: density ≤ 2161/km²); No Development Zone reduced — A: 50 m; B: 200 m from HTL</li>
                <li><strong>CRZ-IV:</strong> water area from LTL up to 12 nautical miles</li>
            </ul>
            Implementation by State CZMAs (Coastal Zone Management Authorities).
        </div>

        <h3>3.3 NOISE POLLUTION (REGULATION &amp; CONTROL) RULES, 2000</h3>
        <table>
            <tr><th>Area Category</th><th>Day (6 AM – 10 PM) dBA</th><th>Night (10 PM – 6 AM) dBA</th></tr>
            <tr><td>Industrial</td><td>75</td><td>70</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Commercial</td><td>65</td><td>55</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Residential</td><td>55</td><td>45</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Silence Zone</strong></td><td>50</td><td>40</td></tr>
        </table>
        <div class="content">
            <strong>Silence zones:</strong> 100 m around hospitals, educational institutions, courts.<br/>
            <strong>Other key provisions:</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>Loudspeakers/PA systems prohibited 10 PM – 6 AM (state may permit relaxation up to 12 midnight on cultural/festive occasions, max 15 days/year)</li>
                <li>Horns of motor vehicles prohibited in silence zones</li>
                <li>Firecrackers banned 10 PM – 6 AM (SC order 2018: only "green crackers" allowed in NCR; 2 hr only on Diwali)</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>3.4 OZONE DEPLETING SUBSTANCES (ODS) RULES, 2000</h3>
        <div class="content">
            Implements <strong>Montreal Protocol (1987)</strong> &amp; <strong>Kigali Amendment (2016)</strong>.
            <ul>
                <li>Phases out CFCs (completed 2010 in India), Halons (2010), CTC, MeCl, MeBr</li>
                <li>HCFCs phase-out: complete by 2030 (India)</li>
                <li>HFCs (added by Kigali) — India to reduce by 80% by 2047</li>
                <li>Mandatory labelling, registration of importers/manufacturers</li>
                <li>Cell: Ozone Cell, MoEFCC</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>3.5 WETLAND (CONSERVATION &amp; MANAGEMENT) RULES, 2017</h3>
        <div class="content">
            <ul>
                <li>Replace Wetland Rules 2010</li>
                <li><strong>Wetlands Authority</strong> at state level (chaired by Environment Minister)</li>
                <li>Brief list of "prohibited activities": conversion to non-wetland use, encroachment, setting up new industries, solid waste disposal, untreated effluent discharge, poaching</li>
                <li>India has <strong>85 Ramsar sites</strong> (as of 2024); largest network in South Asia</li>
                <li>Total area covered: ~13 lakh ha</li>
                <li>Largest Ramsar site in India: <strong>Sundarbans (West Bengal)</strong></li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h2>SECTION 4: INTERNATIONAL CONVENTIONS</h2>
        <div class="section-intro">
            International environmental treaties India is party to. High recall — multiple Qs likely.
        </div>

        <h3>4.1 MAJOR CONVENTIONS — TIMELINE</h3>
        <table>
            <tr><th>Year</th><th>Convention</th><th>Subject</th><th>Hosted at</th></tr>
            <tr><td>1971</td><td><strong>Ramsar Convention</strong></td><td>Wetlands of international importance</td><td>Ramsar, Iran</td></tr>
            <tr><td>1972</td><td><strong>Stockholm Conference</strong> (UNCHE)</td><td>First UN environment conference; UNEP born</td><td>Stockholm</td></tr>
            <tr><td>1972</td><td>London Convention</td><td>Marine dumping</td><td>London</td></tr>
            <tr><td>1973</td><td><strong>CITES</strong></td><td>Trade in endangered species</td><td>Washington DC</td></tr>
            <tr><td>1979</td><td>Bonn (CMS) Convention</td><td>Migratory species</td><td>Bonn</td></tr>
            <tr><td>1985</td><td><strong>Vienna Convention</strong></td><td>Ozone layer (framework)</td><td>Vienna</td></tr>
            <tr><td>1987</td><td><strong>Montreal Protocol</strong></td><td>ODS phase-out (operational)</td><td>Montreal</td></tr>
            <tr><td>1989</td><td><strong>Basel Convention</strong></td><td>Hazardous waste transboundary movement</td><td>Basel</td></tr>
            <tr><td>1992</td><td><strong>Rio Earth Summit (UNCED)</strong></td><td>Birth of UNFCCC, CBD, UNCCD; Agenda 21; Rio Declaration</td><td>Rio de Janeiro</td></tr>
            <tr><td>1992</td><td><strong>UNFCCC</strong></td><td>Climate change framework</td><td>Rio</td></tr>
            <tr><td>1992</td><td><strong>CBD</strong></td><td>Biological diversity</td><td>Rio</td></tr>
            <tr><td>1994</td><td>UNCCD</td><td>Desertification</td><td>Paris</td></tr>
            <tr><td>1997</td><td><strong>Kyoto Protocol</strong></td><td>Binding emissions targets for Annex I (developed)</td><td>Kyoto</td></tr>
            <tr><td>1998</td><td>Rotterdam Convention</td><td>PIC for trade in chemicals/pesticides</td><td>Rotterdam</td></tr>
            <tr><td>2000</td><td>Cartagena Protocol</td><td>Biosafety (LMOs); under CBD</td><td>Cartagena, Colombia</td></tr>
            <tr><td>2001</td><td><strong>Stockholm Convention</strong></td><td>Persistent Organic Pollutants (POPs)</td><td>Stockholm</td></tr>
            <tr><td>2010</td><td>Nagoya Protocol</td><td>ABS; under CBD</td><td>Nagoya, Japan</td></tr>
            <tr><td>2013</td><td>Minamata Convention</td><td>Mercury</td><td>Kumamoto, Japan</td></tr>
            <tr><td>2015</td><td><strong>Paris Agreement</strong></td><td>Climate; NDCs; 1.5°C goal</td><td>Paris (COP 21)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>2016</td><td><strong>Kigali Amendment</strong></td><td>HFC phase-down (under Montreal Protocol)</td><td>Kigali, Rwanda</td></tr>
        </table>

        <h3>4.2 STOCKHOLM CONFERENCE 1972 &amp; FOLLOW-UP</h3>
        <div class="content">
            <strong>UN Conference on Human Environment, Stockholm, 5–16 June 1972.</strong> Tagline: "Only One Earth". Indira Gandhi was the only Head of Government other than the host PM to attend.
            <ul>
                <li>Birthed <strong>UNEP</strong> (UN Environment Programme; HQ Nairobi)</li>
                <li><strong>5 June</strong> declared <strong>World Environment Day</strong></li>
                <li>India enacted Air Act 1981, E(P) Act 1986 in pursuance</li>
            </ul>
            <strong>Subsequent Earth Summits:</strong> Rio 1992; Johannesburg 2002 (Rio+10); Rio 2012 (Rio+20); Stockholm+50 in 2022.
        </div>

        <h3>4.3 CLIMATE — UNFCCC, KYOTO, PARIS</h3>
        <div class="standard">
            <strong>UNFCCC (1992):</strong> framework convention; objective = stabilise GHG concentrations to prevent dangerous anthropogenic interference. India ratified 1993.
            <ul>
                <li>Annex I: developed countries (binding obligations)</li>
                <li>Non-Annex I: developing countries (no binding obligations, but voluntary actions)</li>
                <li><strong>CBDR-RC</strong> = Common But Differentiated Responsibilities &amp; Respective Capabilities</li>
            </ul>
            <strong>Kyoto Protocol (1997, in force 2005):</strong>
            <ul>
                <li>Binding emission cuts for Annex I (~5.2% below 1990 levels by 2008–12; first commitment period)</li>
                <li>3 flexibility mechanisms: <strong>CDM</strong> (Clean Dev Mechanism), <strong>JI</strong> (Joint Implementation), <strong>ET</strong> (Emissions Trading)</li>
                <li>Doha Amendment (2012): 2nd commitment period 2013–20 (limited ratification)</li>
            </ul>
            <strong>Paris Agreement (2015, in force 2016):</strong>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Goal:</strong> well below 2°C above pre-industrial; pursue 1.5°C</li>
                <li><strong>NDCs</strong> (Nationally Determined Contributions): self-set, reviewed every 5 years (ratchet mechanism)</li>
                <li><strong>India's updated NDC (Aug 2022):</strong>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Reduce GDP emissions intensity by 45% by 2030 (from 2005 level)</li>
                        <li>50% cumulative installed capacity from non-fossil fuel by 2030</li>
                        <li>Create additional carbon sink of 2.5–3 billion tonnes CO₂eq through forest cover by 2030</li>
                        <li><strong>Net-zero by 2070</strong> (announced at COP26 Glasgow, 2021 — Panchamrit)</li>
                    </ul>
                </li>
                <li>$100 billion/year climate finance pledge by developed → developing (committed; underdelivered)</li>
                <li><strong>Article 6:</strong> carbon markets (rules finalised at COP26)</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>4.4 OZONE — VIENNA, MONTREAL, KIGALI</h3>
        <div class="content">
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Vienna Convention 1985:</strong> framework; no binding cuts</li>
                <li><strong>Montreal Protocol 1987:</strong> binding phase-out of CFCs, halons, CTC, methyl chloroform, HCFCs (developed by 2020, developing by 2030); methyl bromide</li>
                <li>Universally ratified treaty (197 parties + EU); successful — Antarctic ozone hole expected to close by 2065</li>
                <li><strong>Kigali Amendment 2016:</strong> brings HFCs (high GWP, no ODP) under Montreal; India phase-down 80% by 2047</li>
                <li>India ratified Kigali in 2021</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>4.5 BIODIVERSITY — CBD, NAGOYA, CARTAGENA</h3>
        <div class="content">
            <strong>CBD (1992, Rio):</strong> 3 objectives:
            <ol>
                <li>Conservation of biological diversity</li>
                <li>Sustainable use of components</li>
                <li>Fair &amp; equitable sharing of benefits arising from use of genetic resources (ABS)</li>
            </ol>
            <strong>Cartagena Protocol on Biosafety (2000):</strong> safe transfer/handling of LMOs (living modified organisms); India ratified 2003.<br/>
            <strong>Nagoya Protocol on ABS (2010, in force 2014):</strong> implements 3rd objective of CBD; India ratified 2014.<br/>
            <strong>Aichi Targets (2010, Nagoya):</strong> 20 biodiversity targets for 2011–2020. <strong>Replaced by Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework (Dec 2022):</strong> 23 action targets including <strong>30×30</strong> (protect 30% of land &amp; sea by 2030).
        </div>

        <h3>4.6 CITES (1973, in force 1975)</h3>
        <div class="standard">
            Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora.
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Appendix I:</strong> species threatened with extinction; <span class="key-point">commercial trade BANNED</span> (~1100 species — tiger, rhino, gorilla, elephant)</li>
                <li><strong>Appendix II:</strong> species not necessarily threatened but trade controlled to avoid use incompatible with survival (~37000 species)</li>
                <li><strong>Appendix III:</strong> species protected in at least one country, which has asked others for help (~200 species)</li>
                <li>India ratified 1976; implemented through Wildlife (Protection) Act 1972</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>4.7 BASEL, ROTTERDAM, STOCKHOLM (BRS) "Chemical Conventions"</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Basel (1989):</strong> hazardous waste transboundary movement; PIC; ESM; Ban Amendment in force 2019</li>
            <li><strong>Rotterdam (1998):</strong> PIC for trade in 50+ hazardous chemicals/pesticides</li>
            <li><strong>Stockholm (2001):</strong> POPs — initial 12 ("dirty dozen": aldrin, chlordane, DDT, dieldrin, endrin, heptachlor, mirex, toxaphene, HCB, PCBs, dioxins, furans); later expanded to 30+ chemicals</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>4.8 RAMSAR &amp; OTHER</h3>
        <div class="content">
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Ramsar Convention 1971</strong> (in force 1975): wetlands of international importance; India ratified 1982; <strong>85 Ramsar sites</strong> in India (2024)</li>
                <li><strong>Bonn (CMS) 1979:</strong> migratory species; India ratified 1983</li>
                <li><strong>Minamata Convention 2013</strong> (in force 2017): Mercury — phase-out manufacture/import/export, dental amalgam, batteries; named after Minamata mercury poisoning Japan 1956; India ratified 2018</li>
                <li><strong>UNCCD 1994:</strong> desertification; India hosted COP14 in Sept 2019 (New Delhi Declaration)</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>4.9 PRINCIPLES OF INTERNATIONAL ENVIRONMENTAL LAW <span style="color:#673ab7;">(GATE ADD)</span></h3>
        <div class="standard">
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Sustainable Development:</strong> "development that meets the needs of the present without compromising the ability of future generations to meet their own needs" — Brundtland Report 1987 ("Our Common Future")</li>
                <li><strong>Polluter Pays Principle (PPP):</strong> polluter bears cost of pollution control + damage; first articulated by OECD 1972; SC adopted in <em>Indian Council for Enviro-Legal Action v UoI</em> (1996)</li>
                <li><strong>Precautionary Principle:</strong> lack of full scientific certainty shall not be a reason to postpone cost-effective measures to prevent environmental degradation; Rio Principle 15; SC adopted in <em>Vellore Citizens Welfare Forum v UoI</em> (1996)</li>
                <li><strong>Public Trust Doctrine:</strong> certain resources (rivers, seashores, forests) held in trust by state for public use; SC in <em>MC Mehta v Kamal Nath</em> (1997, Span Motels)</li>
                <li><strong>Inter-generational Equity:</strong> present generation has duty to preserve resources for future; <em>State of HP v Ganesh Wood Products</em> (1995)</li>
                <li><strong>Common but Differentiated Responsibilities (CBDR):</strong> all states responsible but with differing capabilities (Rio 1992)</li>
                <li><strong>Absolute Liability:</strong> stricter than strict liability; no exceptions; SC in <em>MC Mehta v UoI</em> (Oleum Gas Leak, 1986)</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>4.10 NATIONAL ENVIRONMENT POLICY (NEP) 2006 <span style="color:#673ab7;">(GATE ADD)</span></h3>
        <div class="content">
            Approved by Union Cabinet in May 2006.<br/>
            <strong>Key principles:</strong> Human beings at centre of sustainable development; Right to development; Environmental protection integral to development; Polluter Pays; Precautionary; PPP (public participation); Decentralisation; Equity.<br/>
            <strong>Strategic actions:</strong> conservation of biodiversity, climate change mitigation, water resource management, freshwater ecosystems, pollution control, mountain ecosystems, coastal management.<br/>
            <strong>NEP is a policy guideline (not legally binding)</strong> — informs subsequent rules &amp; programs.
        </div>

